events.description: Siege of Rome: The Ostrogoth army under king Vitiges begins the siege of the capital. Belisarius conducts a delaying action outside the Flaminian Gate; he and a detachment of his bucellarii are almost cut off.
events.html: • 537 – Siege of Rome: The Ostrogoth army under king Vitiges begins the siege of the capital. Belisarius conducts a delaying action outside the Flaminian Gate; he and a detachment of his bucellarii are almost cut off.[1]

events.description: Louis V becomes the last Carolingian king of West Francia after the death of his father, Lothaire.
events.html: • 986 – Louis V becomes the last Carolingian king of West Francia after the death of his father, Lothaire.[2]

events.description: Fall of Nicaea to the Ottoman Turks after a siege.
events.html: • 1331 – Fall of Nicaea to the Ottoman Turks after a siege.[3]

events.description: Skanderbeg organizes a group of Albanian nobles to form the League of Lezhë.
events.html: • 1444 – Skanderbeg organizes a group of Albanian nobles to form the League of Lezhë.[4]

events.description: George of Poděbrady is chosen as the king of Bohemia.
events.html: • 1458 – George of Poděbrady is chosen as the king of Bohemia.[5]

events.description: Burgundian Wars: The Old Swiss Confederacy hands Charles the Bold, Duke of Burgundy, a major defeat in the Battle of Grandson in Canton of Neuchâtel.
events.html: • 1476 – Burgundian Wars: The Old Swiss Confederacy hands Charles the Bold, Duke of Burgundy, a major defeat in the Battle of Grandson in Canton of Neuchâtel.[6]

events.description: The College of Arms is formally incorporated by Royal Charter signed by King Richard III of England.
events.html: • 1484 – The College of Arms is formally incorporated by Royal Charter signed by King Richard III of England.[7]

events.description: Vasco da Gama's fleet visits the Island of Mozambique.
events.html: • 1498 – Vasco da Gama's fleet visits the Island of Mozambique.[8]

events.description: The Great Fire of Meireki begins in Edo (now Tokyo), Japan, causing more than 100,000 deaths before it exhausts itself three days later.
events.html: • 1657 – The Great Fire of Meireki begins in Edo (now Tokyo), Japan, causing more than 100,000 deaths before it exhausts itself three days later.

events.description: American Revolutionary War: Patriot militia units attempt to prevent capture of supply ships in and around the Savannah River by a small fleet of the Royal Navy in the Battle of the Rice Boats.
events.html: • 1776 – American Revolutionary War: Patriot militia units attempt to prevent capture of supply ships in and around the Savannah River by a small fleet of the Royal Navy in the Battle of the Rice Boats.[9]

events.description: Claude Chappe demonstrates the first semaphore line near Paris.
events.html: • 1791 – Claude Chappe demonstrates the first semaphore line near Paris.

events.description: The Bank of England issues the first one-pound and two-pound banknotes.
events.html: • 1797 – The Bank of England issues the first one-pound and two-pound banknotes.

events.description: The U.S. Congress passes the Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves, disallowing the importation of new slaves into the country.
events.html: • 1807 – The U.S. Congress passes the Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves, disallowing the importation of new slaves into the country.

events.description: Argentine War of Independence: A royalist fleet defeats a small flotilla of revolutionary ships in the Battle of San Nicolás on the River Plate.
events.html: • 1811 – Argentine War of Independence: A royalist fleet defeats a small flotilla of revolutionary ships in the Battle of San Nicolás on the River Plate.

events.description: Signing of the Kandyan Convention treaty by British invaders and the leaders of the Kingdom of Kandy.
events.html: • 1815 – Signing of the Kandyan Convention treaty by British invaders and the leaders of the Kingdom of Kandy.

events.description: Texas Revolution: The Declaration of independence of the Republic of Texas from Mexico is adopted.
events.html: • 1836 – Texas Revolution: The Declaration of independence of the Republic of Texas from Mexico is adopted.

events.description: Alexander II becomes Tsar of Russia.
events.html: • 1855 – Alexander II becomes Tsar of Russia.

events.description: The two-day Great Slave Auction, the largest such auction in United States history, begins.
events.html: • 1859 – The two-day Great Slave Auction, the largest such auction in United States history, begins.

events.description: East Cape War: The Völkner Incident in New Zealand.
events.html: • 1865 – East Cape War: The Völkner Incident in New Zealand.

events.description: The U.S. Congress passes the first Reconstruction Act.
events.html: • 1867 – The U.S. Congress passes the first Reconstruction Act.

events.description: Just two days before inauguration, the U.S. Congress declares Rutherford B. Hayes the winner of the 1876 U.S. presidential election even though Samuel J. Tilden had won the popular vote.
events.html: • 1877 – Just two days before inauguration, the U.S. Congress declares Rutherford B. Hayes the winner of the 1876 U.S. presidential election even though Samuel J. Tilden had won the popular vote.

events.description: Queen Victoria narrowly escapes an assassination attempt by Roderick Maclean in Windsor.
events.html: • 1882 – Queen Victoria narrowly escapes an assassination attempt by Roderick Maclean in Windsor.

events.description: United States Steel Corporation is founded as a result of a merger between Carnegie Steel Company and Federal Steel Company which became the first corporation in the world with a market capital over $1 billion.
events.html: • 1901 – United States Steel Corporation is founded as a result of a merger between Carnegie Steel Company and Federal Steel Company which became the first corporation in the world with a market capital over $1 billion.

events.description: The U.S. Congress passes the Platt Amendment limiting the autonomy of Cuba, as a condition of the withdrawal of American troops.
events.html: • 1901 – The U.S. Congress passes the Platt Amendment limiting the autonomy of Cuba, as a condition of the withdrawal of American troops.

events.description: In New York City the Martha Washington Hotel opens, becoming the first hotel exclusively for women.
events.html: • 1903 – In New York City the Martha Washington Hotel opens, becoming the first hotel exclusively for women.

events.description: The enactment of the Jones–Shafroth Act grants Puerto Ricans United States citizenship.
events.html: • 1917 – The enactment of the Jones–Shafroth Act grants Puerto Ricans United States citizenship.

events.description: The first Communist International meets in Moscow.
events.html: • 1919 – The first Communist International meets in Moscow.[10]

events.description: Finnish president P. E. Svinhufvud gives a radio speech, which four days later finally ends the Mäntsälä Rebellion and the far-right Lapua Movement that started it.
events.html: • 1932 – Finnish president P. E. Svinhufvud gives a radio speech, which four days later finally ends the Mäntsälä Rebellion and the far-right Lapua Movement that started it.[11][12]

events.description: The Steel Workers Organizing Committee signs a collective bargaining agreement with U.S. Steel, leading to unionization of the United States steel industry.
events.html: • 1937 – The Steel Workers Organizing Committee signs a collective bargaining agreement with U.S. Steel, leading to unionization of the United States steel industry.[13]

events.description: Cardinal Eugenio Pacelli is elected Pope and takes the name Pius XII.
events.html: • 1939 – Cardinal Eugenio Pacelli is elected Pope and takes the name Pius XII.[14]

events.description: World War II: First German military units enter Bulgaria after it joins the Axis Pact.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: First German military units enter Bulgaria after it joins the Axis Pact.

entities.name: Military history of Bulgaria during World War II

events.description: World War II: During the Battle of the Bismarck Sea Allied aircraft defeated a Japanese attempt to ship troops to New Guinea.
events.html: • 1943 – World War II: During the Battle of the Bismarck Sea Allied aircraft defeated a Japanese attempt to ship troops to New Guinea.

events.description: Captain James Gallagher lands his B-50 Superfortress Lucky Lady II in Fort Worth, Texas, after completing the first non-stop around-the-world airplane flight in 94 hours and one minute.
events.html: • 1949 – Captain James Gallagher lands his B-50 Superfortress Lucky Lady II in Fort Worth, Texas, after completing the first non-stop around-the-world airplane flight in 94 hours and one minute.[15]

events.description: Norodom Sihanouk, king of Cambodia, abdicates the throne in favor of his father, Norodom Suramarit.
events.html: • 1955 – Norodom Sihanouk, king of Cambodia, abdicates the throne in favor of his father, Norodom Suramarit.[16]

events.description: In Burma, the army led by General Ne Win seizes power in a coup d'état.
events.html: • 1962 – In Burma, the army led by General Ne Win seizes power in a coup d'état.[17]

events.description: Wilt Chamberlain sets the single-game scoring record in the National Basketball Association by scoring 100 points.
events.html: • 1962 – Wilt Chamberlain sets the single-game scoring record in the National Basketball Association by scoring 100 points.[18]

events.description: The US and Republic of Vietnam Air Force begin Operation Rolling Thunder, a sustained bombing campaign against North Vietnam.
events.html: • 1965 – The US and Republic of Vietnam Air Force begin Operation Rolling Thunder, a sustained bombing campaign against North Vietnam.[19]

events.description: Baggeridge Colliery closes marking the end of over 300 years of coal mining in the Black Country.
events.html: • 1968 – Baggeridge Colliery closes marking the end of over 300 years of coal mining in the Black Country.[20]

events.description: In Toulouse, France, the first test flight of the Anglo-French Concorde is conducted.
events.html: • 1969 – In Toulouse, France, the first test flight of the Anglo-French Concorde is conducted.[21]

events.description: Rhodesia declares itself a republic, breaking its last links with the British crown.
events.html: • 1970 – Rhodesia declares itself a republic, breaking its last links with the British crown.[22]

events.description: The Pioneer 10 space probe is launched from Cape Canaveral, Florida with a mission to explore the outer planets.
events.html: • 1972 – The Pioneer 10 space probe is launched from Cape Canaveral, Florida with a mission to explore the outer planets.[23]

events.description: Libya becomes the Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya as the General People's Congress adopted the "Declaration on the Establishment of the Authority of the People".
events.html: • 1977 – Libya becomes the Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya as the General People's Congress adopted the "Declaration on the Establishment of the Authority of the People".[24]

entities.name: Declaration on the Establishment of the Authority of the People

events.description: Czech Vladimír Remek becomes the first non-Russian or non-American to go into space, when he is launched aboard Soyuz 28.
events.html: • 1978 – Czech Vladimír Remek becomes the first non-Russian or non-American to go into space, when he is launched aboard Soyuz 28.[25]

events.description: The late iconic actor Charlie Chaplin's coffin is stolen from his grave in Switzerland.
events.html: • 1978 – The late iconic actor Charlie Chaplin's coffin is stolen from his grave in Switzerland.[26]

events.description: Compact discs and players are released for the first time in the United States and other markets. They had previously been available only in Japan.
events.html: • 1983 – Compact discs and players are released for the first time in the United States and other markets.[27] They had previously been available only in Japan.[28]

events.description: Twelve European Community nations agree to ban the production of all chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) by the end of the century.
events.html: • 1989 – Twelve European Community nations agree to ban the production of all chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) by the end of the century.[29]

events.description: Nelson Mandela is elected deputy president of the African National Congress.
events.html: • 1990 – Nelson Mandela is elected deputy president of the African National Congress.[30]

events.description: Establishment of Kuwait Democratic Forum, center-left political organization in Kuwait.
events.html: • 1991 – Establishment of Kuwait Democratic Forum, center-left political organization in Kuwait.[31]

events.description: Battle at Rumaila oil field brings an end to the 1991 Gulf War.
events.html: • 1991 – Battle at Rumaila oil field brings an end to the 1991 Gulf War.

events.description: Start of the war in Transnistria.
events.html: • 1992 – Start of the war in Transnistria.

events.description: Armenia, Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, San Marino, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan, all of which (except San Marino) were former Soviet republics, join the United Nations.
events.html: • 1992 – Armenia, Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, San Marino, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan, all of which (except San Marino) were former Soviet republics, join the United Nations.

events.description: Researchers at Fermilab announce the discovery of the top quark.
events.html: • 1995 – Researchers at Fermilab announce the discovery of the top quark.

events.description: Data sent from the Galileo spacecraft indicates that Jupiter's moon Europa has a liquid ocean under a thick crust of ice.
events.html: • 1998 – Data sent from the Galileo spacecraft indicates that Jupiter's moon Europa has a liquid ocean under a thick crust of ice.

events.description: U.S. invasion of Afghanistan: Operation Anaconda begins, (ending on March 19 after killing 500 Taliban and al-Qaeda fighters, with 11 Western troop fatalities).
events.html: • 2002 – U.S. invasion of Afghanistan: Operation Anaconda begins, (ending on March 19 after killing 500 Taliban and al-Qaeda fighters, with 11 Western troop fatalities).

events.description: War in Iraq: Al-Qaeda carries out the Ashoura Massacre in Iraq, killing 170 and wounding over 500.
events.html: • 2004 – War in Iraq: Al-Qaeda carries out the Ashoura Massacre in Iraq, killing 170 and wounding over 500.

events.description: A tornado outbreak occurs over a large section of the Southern United States and into the Ohio Valley region, resulting in 40 tornado-related fatalities.
events.html: • 2012 – A tornado outbreak occurs over a large section of the Southern United States and into the Ohio Valley region, resulting in 40 tornado-related fatalities.

events.description: The elements Moscovium, Tennessine, and Oganesson are officially added to the periodic table at a conference in Moscow, Russia.
events.html: • 2017 – The elements Moscovium, Tennessine, and Oganesson are officially added to the periodic table at a conference in Moscow, Russia.

events.description: Russian forces capture the city of Kherson during the Russian invasion of Ukraine, which subsequently began the start of the Russian occupation and military-civilian administration in Kherson. Kherson is the only regional capital in Ukraine that Russia captured.
events.html: • 2022 – Russian forces capture the city of Kherson during the Russian invasion of Ukraine, which subsequently began the start of the Russian occupation and military-civilian administration in Kherson.[32] Kherson is the only regional capital in Ukraine that Russia captured.
